A named list with elements \code{index_node} and \code{parameter}.
}
\subsection{Examples}{
\if{html}{\out{<div class="r example copy">}}
\preformatted{\dontrun{
q$state()
q$state(null = TRUE)
}
}
\if{html}{\out{</div>}}

}

}
\if{html}{\out{<hr>}}
\if{html}{\out{<a id="method-EsgQuery-reset"></a>}}
\if{latex}{\out{\hypertarget{method-EsgQuery-reset}{}}}
\subsection{Method \code{reset()}}{
Reset query parameters to their defaults.

\verb{$reset()} clears the current parameter store and restores the default
query parameters. The current index node is kept unchanged.
\subsection{Usage}{
\if{html}{\out{<div class="r">}}\preformatted{EsgQuery$reset()}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}
}

\subsection{Returns}{
The modified \code{EsgQuery} object itself.
}
\subsection{Examples}{
\if{html}{\out{<div class="r example copy">}}
\preformatted{\dontrun{
q$experiment_id("ssp585")$reset()
}
}
\if{html}{\out{</div>}}

}

}
\if{html}{\out{<hr>}}
\if{html}{\out{<a id="method-EsgQuery-save"></a>}}
\if{latex}{\out{\hypertarget{method-EsgQuery-save}{}}}
\subsection{Method \code{save()}}{
Save the query into a JSON file

\verb{$save()} puts main data of an \code{EsgQuery} object into a JSON file
which can be loaded to restore the current state of query using
\href{#method-EsgQuery-load}{\code{EsgQuery$load()}}.
\subsection{Usage}{
\if{html}{\out{<div class="r">}}\preformatted{EsgQuery$save(file = "query.json", pretty = TRUE)}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}
}

\subsection{Arguments}{
\if{html}{\out{<div class="arguments">}}
\describe{
\item{\code{file}}{A string indicating the JSON file path to save the data
to.}

\item{\code{pretty}}{Whether to add indentation whitespace to JSON output.
For details, please see \code{\link[jsonlite:fromJSON]{jsonlite::toJSON()}}. Default: \code{TRUE}.}
}
\if{html}{\out{</div>}}
}
\subsection{Returns}{
The full path of the output JSON file.
}
\subsection{Examples}{
\if{html}{\out{<div class="r example copy">}}
\preformatted{\dontrun{
q$save(tempfile(fileext = ".json"))
}
}
\if{html}{\out{</div>}}

}

}
\if{html}{\out{<hr>}}
\if{html}{\out{<a id="method-EsgQuery-load"></a>}}
\if{latex}{\out{\hypertarget{method-EsgQuery-load}{}}}
\subsection{Method \code{load()}}{
Restore the query state from an JSON file

\verb{$load()} reads data of an \code{EsgQuery} object from a JSON file
created using
\href{#method-EsgQuery-save}{\code{EsgQuery$save()}}.
\subsection{Usage}{
\if{html}{\out{<div class="r">}}\preformatted{EsgQuery$load(file)}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}
}

\subsection{Arguments}{
\if{html}{\out{<div class="arguments">}}
\describe{
\item{\code{file}}{A string indicating the JSON file path to read the data
from.}
}
\if{html}{\out{</div>}}
}
\subsection{Returns}{
The modified \code{EsgQuery} object itself.
}
\subsection{Examples}{
\if{html}{\out{<div class="r example copy">}}
\preformatted{\dontrun{
f <- tempfile(fileext = "json")

q <- esg_query()
json <- q$save(f)
q$load(f)
}
}
\if{html}{\out{</div>}}

}

}
